[{"location":"apiref/#API-Reference","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"apiref/","page":"API Reference","title":"API Reference","text":"Modules = [SphericalScattering]","category":"page"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.ε0","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.ε0","text":"ε0 = 8.8541878176e-12\n\nFree space permittivity.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"constant"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.μ0","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.μ0","text":"μ0 = 4pi * 1e-7\n\nFree space permeability.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"constant"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.DielectricSphere-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.DielectricSphere","text":"DielectricSphere(\n    radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"), \n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0), \n    filling     = error(\"missing argument `filling`\")\n)\n\nConstructor for the dielectric sphere.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer","text":"DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer(\n    radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"),\n    thickness   = error(\"missing argument `thickness` of the coating\"),\n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n    thinlayer   = error(\"missing argument `thinlayer`\"),\n    filling     = error(\"missing argument `filling`\")\n)\n\nConstructor for the dielectric sphere with a thin impedance layer. For this model, it is assumed that the displacement field is only radial direction in the layer, which requires a small thickness and low conductivity. For details, see for example T. B. Jones, Ed., “Models for layered spherical particles,” in Electromechanics of Particles, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1995,  pp. 227–235. doi: 10.1017/CBO9780511574498.012.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.FitzgeraldDipole-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.FitzgeraldDipole","text":"ex = FitzgeraldDipole(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        position    = error(\"missing argument `position`\"),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.HertzianDipole-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.HertzianDipole","text":"ex = HertzianDipole(\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        position    = error(\"missing argument `position`\"),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.LayeredSphere-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.LayeredSphere","text":"LayeredSphere( \n    radii       = error(\"Missing argument `radii`\"), \n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0), \n    filling     = error(\"`missing argument `filling`\")\n)\n\nConstructor for the layered dielectric sphere.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.LayeredSpherePEC-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.LayeredSpherePEC","text":"LayeredSpherePEC( \n    radii       = error(\"Missing argument `radii`\"), \n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0), \n    filling     = error(\"Missing argument `filling`\")\n)\n\nConstructor for the layered dielectric sphere.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.Medium","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.Medium","text":"Medium(ε, μ)\n\nHomogeneous, isotropic background medium.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.PECSphere-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.PECSphere","text":"PECSphere( \n    radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"), \n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0)\n)\n\nConstructor for the PEC sphere.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.SphericalModeTE-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.SphericalModeTE","text":"ex = SphericalModeTE(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        m           = 0,\n        n           = 1,\n        c           = 1,\n        center      = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 0.0),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.SphericalModeTM-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.SphericalModeTM","text":"ex = SphericalModeTM(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        m           = 0,\n        n           = 1,\n        c           = 1,\n        center      = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 0.0),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.UniformField-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.UniformField","text":"ex = UniformField(; \n    embedding=Medium(ε0, μ0), \n    amplitude=1.0, \n    direction=SVector{3,typeof(amplitude)}(1.0, 0.0, 0.0)\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.amplitude-Tuple{Any, PlaneWave, ElectricField, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.amplitude","text":"amplitude(sphere, excitation::PlaneWave, quantity::MagneticField, r)\n\nReturns E₀, where E₀ is the electric field of the incident plane wave. For PEC layers, it returns 0.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.amplitude-Tuple{Any, PlaneWave, FarField, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.amplitude","text":"amplitude(sphere, excitation::PlaneWave, quantity::MagneticField, r)\n\nReturns E₀, where E₀ is the electric field of the incident plane wave.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.amplitude-Tuple{Any, PlaneWave, MagneticField, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.amplitude","text":"amplitude(sphere, excitation::PlaneWave, quantity::MagneticField, r)\n\nReturns H₀ηᵢ, where H₀ is the magnetic field of the incident plane wave. For PEC layers, it returns 0.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.associatedLegendre-Union{Tuple{F}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{T, T, F}} where {T<:Integer, F<:Real}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.associatedLegendre","text":"associatedLegendre(n::T, m::T, ϑ::F)\n\nCompute the normalized associated Legendre polynomials according to the definition by Hansen (A1.25) times m divided by sin(ϑ),  but including the Condon-Shortley phase. By using the recursion relations (A1.34a) all corner cases are accounted for correctly.\n\nm * bar(P)n|m|(cos(ϑ)) / sin(ϑ)\n\nϑ ∈ [0, π] assumed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.cart2sph-Tuple{Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.cart2sph","text":"cart2sph(vec)\n\nConvert a 3D (3 entry) point from Cartesian to spherical coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.convertSpherical2Cartesian-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.convertSpherical2Cartesian","text":"convertSpherical2Cartesian(F_sph, point_sph)\n\nTakes a 3D (3 entry) vector F_sph and converts it from its spherical basis to its Cartesian basis representation.\n\nThe location of the vector has to be provided in spherical coordinates by point_sph ordered as (r ϑ φ).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.derivatieAssociatedLegendre-Union{Tuple{F}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{T, T, F}} where {T<:Integer, F<:Real}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.derivatieAssociatedLegendre","text":"derivatieAssociatedLegendre(n::T, m::T, ϑ::F) where {T<:Integer,F<:Real}\n\nCompute the derivatives of the normalized associated Legendre polynomials according to the definition by Hansen (A1.25),  but including the Condon-Shortley phase. By using the recursion relations (A1.34b) all corner cases are accounted for correctly.\n\nd bar(P)n|m|(cos(ϑ)) / dϑ\n\nϑ ∈ [0, π] assumed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.electricRingCurrent-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.electricRingCurrent","text":"ex = electricRingCurrent(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"),\n        center      = error(\"missing argument `center`\"),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.expansion-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Sphere, PlaneWave, SphericalScattering.Field, Any, Any, Any, Any, Int64}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.expansion","text":"expansion(sphere::Sphere, excitation::PlaneWave, quantity::Field, r, plm, cosϑ, sinϑ, n::Int)\n\nCompute functional dependencies of the Mie series for a plane wave travelling in +z-direction with polarization in x-direction.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{FitzgeraldDipole, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::FitzgeraldDipole, point, quantity::FarField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric far field radiated by a Fitzgerald dipole at given position and orientation at point.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{HertzianDipole, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::HertzianDipole, point, quantity::FarField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric far field radiated by a Hertzian dipole at given position and orientation at point.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{PlaneWave, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::PlaneWave, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field of a plane wave.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{PlaneWave, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::PlaneWave, point, quantity::FarField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nThrow error since the far-field of a plane wave is not defined.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{PlaneWave, Any, MagneticField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::PlaneWave, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the magnetic field of a plane wave.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{PlaneWave, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::PlaneWave, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field of a plane wave.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalMode, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::SphericalMode, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field of a spherical mode.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalModeTE, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::SphericalModeTE, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field of a TE spherical mode.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalModeTE, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::SphericalModeTE, point, quantity::FarField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric far-field of a TE spherical mode.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalModeTM, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::SphericalModeTE, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field of a TM spherical mode. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalModeTM, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::SphericalModeTE, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric far-field of a TM spherical mode. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Dipole, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::Dipole, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field radiated by a Hertzian dipole at given position and orientation at point.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Dipole, Any, MagneticField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::Dipole, point, quantity::MagneticField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the magnetic field radiated by a Hertzian dipole at given position and orientation at point.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Dipole, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::Dipole, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field radiated by a magnetic/electric ring current at some position and with some orientation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.RingCurrent, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::ElectricRingCurrent, r, ϑ, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field radiated by an electric ring current placed in origin at point (r, ϑ) \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.RingCurrent, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::ElectricRingCurrent, r, ϑ, quantity::FarField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the (electric) far-field radiated by an electric ring current placed in origin at point (r, ϑ) \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.RingCurrent, Any, MagneticField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::ElectricRingCurrent, r, ϑ, quantity::MagneticField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the magnetic field radiated by an electric ring current placed in origin at point (r, ϑ) \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.RingCurrent, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::RingCurrent, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field radiated by a magnetic/electric ring current at some position and with some orientation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Sphere, Excitation, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(sphere::Sphere, excitation::Excitation, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the total field in the presence of a sphere for a given excitation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Sphere, PlaneWave, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(sphere::Sphere, excitation::PlaneWave, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nDescriptive error for the total far-field in the presence of a sphere for an incident plane wave.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Sphere, SphericalMode, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(sphere::Sphere, excitation::SphericalMode, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nDescriptive error for the total far-field in the presence of a sphere for an incident spherical mode.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{UniformField, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field of a uniform field.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{UniformField, Any, ScalarPotential}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ScalarPotential; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the scalar potential of a uniform field.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.field-Tuple{UniformField, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.field","text":"field(excitation::UniformField, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the field or potential of a uniform field.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.getFieldType-Tuple{ElectricRingCurrent, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.getFieldType","text":"getFieldType(excitation::ElectricRingCurrent, quantity::Field)\n\nDo nothing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.getFieldType-Tuple{FitzgeraldDipole, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.getFieldType","text":"getFieldType(excitation::FitzgeraldDipole, quantity::Field)\n\nExchange electric and magnetic field for a magnetic current + apply duality relations.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.getFieldType-Tuple{HertzianDipole, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.getFieldType","text":"getFieldType(excitation::HertzianDipole, quantity::Field)\n\nDo nothing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.getFieldType-Tuple{MagneticRingCurrent, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.getFieldType","text":"getFieldType(excitation::MagneticRingCurrent, quantity::Field)\n\nExchange electric and magnetic field for a magnetic current.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.getFieldType-Tuple{SphericalMode, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.getFieldType","text":"getFieldType(excitation::SphericalMode, quantity::ElectricField)\n\nDo nothing.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.getFieldType-Tuple{SphericalModeTE, MagneticField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.getFieldType","text":"getFieldType(excitation::SphericalModeTE, quantity::MagneticField)\n\nExchange TE and TM. Other prefactor: im / ZF.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.getFieldType-Tuple{SphericalModeTM, MagneticField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.getFieldType","text":"getFieldType(excitation::SphericalModeTM, quantity::MagneticField)\n\nExchange TE and TM. Other prefactor: im / ZF.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.layer-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Sphere, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.layer","text":"layer(sp::Sphere, r)\n\nReturns the index of the layer, r is located, where 1 denotes the inner most layer. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.magneticRingCurrent-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.magneticRingCurrent","text":"ex = magneticRingCurrent(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"),\n        center      = error(\"missing argument `center`\"),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.phiCutPoints-Tuple{Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.phiCutPoints","text":"phiCutPoints(ϕ; r=1.0, resolution=1)\n\nConvenience function returning points (in Cartesian coordinates) on a phi cut at a distance 'r' and a resolution in degrees. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.planeWave-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Sphere}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.planeWave","text":"ex = planeWave(\n        sp::Sphere;\n        frequency    = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude    = 1.0,\n        direction    = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n        polarization = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(1.0, 0.0, 0.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.planeWave-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.planeWave","text":"ex = planeWave(;\n        embedding    = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency    = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude    = 1.0,\n        direction    = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n        polarization = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(1.0, 0.0, 0.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.prefac-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{T, T}} where T<:Integer","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.prefac","text":"prefac(m::T, n::T)\n\nPrefactor for both types of spherical vector wave functions.\n\nNote the factor (-m / abs(m))^m is now part of the associated Legendre polynomials via the Condon-Shortley phase.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.rotate!-Tuple{Excitation, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.rotate!","text":"rotate!(excitation::Excitation, vectors_list; inverse=false)\n\nDetermine rotation matrix and perform rotation for a general excitation. \n\nThe points are assumed to be in Cartesian coordinates.\n\nThe vectors_list IS modified (overwritten).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.rotate-Tuple{Excitation, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.rotate","text":"rotate(excitation::Excitation, vectors_list; inverse=false)\n\nDetermine rotation matrix and perform rotation for general excitations. \n\nThe points are assumed to be in Cartesian coordinates.\n\nThe vectors_list is NOT modified.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.rotationMatrix-Tuple{PlaneWave}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.rotationMatrix","text":"rotationMatrix(excitation::PlaneWave)\n\nDetermine rotation matrix for a plane wave excitation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.rotationMatrix-Tuple{Union{SphericalScattering.Dipole, SphericalScattering.RingCurrent, UniformField}}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.rotationMatrix","text":"rotationMatrix(excitation::Union{Dipole,RingCurrent})\n\nDetermine rotation matrix for a dipole or a ring-current excitation via the Rodrigues formula. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff-Tuple{DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, UniformField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff","text":"scatterCoeff(sp::DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, ex::UniformField)\n\nCompute the expansion coefficients for the thin impedance layer case and a uniform static field excitation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff-Tuple{PECSphere, ElectricRingCurrent, Int64, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff","text":"scatterCoeff(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::ElectricRingCurrent, n::Int, ka)\n\nCompute scattering coefficient for electric ring current.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff-Tuple{PECSphere, FitzgeraldDipole, Int64, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff","text":"scatterCoeff(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::FitzgeraldDipole, n::Int, ka)\n\nCompute scattering coefficient for Fitzgerald dipole.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff-Tuple{PECSphere, HertzianDipole, Int64, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff","text":"scatterCoeff(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::HertzianDipole, n::Int, ka)\n\nCompute scattering coefficient for Hertzian dipole.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff-Tuple{PECSphere, MagneticRingCurrent, Int64, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff","text":"scatterCoeff(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::MagneticRingCurrent, n::Int, ka)\n\nCompute scattering coefficient for magnetic ring current.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff-Tuple{PECSphere, PlaneWave, Int64}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff","text":"scatterCoeff(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::PlaneWave, n::Int)\n\nCompute scattering coefficients for a plane wave travelling in +z-direction  with polarization in x-direction.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalModeTE, Int64, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff","text":"scatterCoeff(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::SphericalModeTE, n::Int, ka)\n\nCompute scattering coefficients for a spherical TE mode travelling towards the origin.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalModeTM, Int64, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff","text":"scatterCoeff(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::SphericalModeTM, n::Int, ka)\n\nCompute scattering coefficients for a spherical TM mode travelling towards the origin.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff_of_layer-Tuple{Any, Any, Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatterCoeff_of_layer","text":"scatterCoeff_of_layer(sphere, r, coeffs)\n\nGiven a tuple of scattering coefficients coeffs, it returns the two scattering coefficients of the layer to which r belongs.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{DielectricSphere, UniformField, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::DielectricSphere, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a Dielectric sphere, for an incident uniform field with polarization in given direction.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{DielectricSphere, UniformField, Any, ScalarPotential}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::DielectricSphere, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ScalarPotential; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the scalar potential scattered by a Dielectric sphere, for an incident uniform field with polarization in given direction.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, UniformField, Any, DisplacementField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::DisplacementField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the displacement field D = ε * E.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, UniformField, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a dielectric sphere with a thin coating, where the displacement field in the coating is only in radial direction. We assume an an incident uniform field with polarization in the given direction.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, UniformField, Any, ScalarPotentialJump}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ScalarPotentialJump; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the jump of the scalar potential for a dielectric sphere with a thin coating, where the displacement field in the coating is only in radial direction. We assume an an incident uniform field with polarization in the given direction.\n\nMore precisely, we compute the difference Δ = Φi - Φe, where Φi is the potential on the inner side and ϕe the exterior potential.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, UniformField, Any, ScalarPotential}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ScalarPotential; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the scalar potential scattered by a dielectric sphere with a thin coating, where the displacement field in the coating is only in radial direction. We assume an an incident uniform field with polarization in the given direction.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, ElectricRingCurrent, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::ElectricRingCurrent, quantity::FarField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric far-field scattered by the PEC sphere, where the ring current is placed along the z-axis.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, FitzgeraldDipole, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::FitzgeraldDipole, quantity::FarField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric far-field scattered by a PEC sphere, where the dipole is placed along the z-axis at z0.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, HertzianDipole, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::HertzianDipole, quantity::FarField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric far-field scattered by a PEC sphere, where the dipole is placed along the z-axis at z0.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, MagneticRingCurrent, Any, FarField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::MagneticRingCurrent, quantity::FarField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric far-field scattered by the PEC sphere, where the ring current is placed along the z-axis.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalMode, Any, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::SphericalModeTE, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a PEC sphere, when excited by a spherical mode travelling towards the origin.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalMode, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::SphericalMode, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a dipole at some position and orientation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalScattering.Dipole, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::Dipole, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a PEC sphere, where the dipole is placed along the z-axis at z0.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalScattering.Dipole, Any, MagneticField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::Dipole, point, quantity::MagneticField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the magnetic field scattered by a PEC sphere, where the dipole is placed along the z-axis at z0.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalScattering.Dipole, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::Dipole, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the field scattered by a PEC sphere excited by a dipole at some position and orientation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalScattering.RingCurrent, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::RingCurrent, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by the PEC sphere, where the ring current is placed along the z-axis.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalScattering.RingCurrent, Any, MagneticField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::RingCurrent, quantity::MagneticField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the magnetic field scattered by the PEC sphere, where the ring current is placed along the z-axis.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, SphericalScattering.RingCurrent, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"field(excitation::ElectricRingCurrent, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field radiated by an electric ring current at some position and orientation\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, UniformField, Any, ElectricField}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a PEC sphere, for an incident uniform field with polarization in the given direction.\n\nThe point and returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{PECSphere, UniformField, Any, ScalarPotential}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::PECSphere, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ScalarPotential; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the scalar potential scattered by a PEC sphere, for an incident uniform field with polarization in the given direction.\n\nThe point and returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Sphere, PlaneWave, Any, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::Sphere, excitation::PlaneWave, point, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a PEC or dielectric sphere, for an incident plane wave travelling in +z-direction with E-field polarization in x-direction.\n\nThe point and the returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Sphere, PlaneWave, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::Sphere, excitation::PlaneWave, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a PEC sphere, for an incident plane wave.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Tuple{SphericalScattering.Sphere, UniformField, SphericalScattering.Field}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::Sphere, excitation::PlaneWave, quantity::Field; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a sphere, for an incident uniform field.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Union{Tuple{FR}, Tuple{FT}, Tuple{FC}, Tuple{LC}, Tuple{LR}, Tuple{LD}, Tuple{LN}, Tuple{LayeredSpherePEC{LN, LD, LR, LC}, UniformField{FC, FT, FR}, Any, ElectricField}} where {LN, LD, LR, LC, FC, FT, FR}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::LayeredSpherePEC, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a layered dielectric sphere with PEC core, for an incident uniform field with polarization in the given direction.\n\nThe point and returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Union{Tuple{FR}, Tuple{FT}, Tuple{FC}, Tuple{LC}, Tuple{LR}, Tuple{LD}, Tuple{LN}, Tuple{LayeredSpherePEC{LN, LD, LR, LC}, UniformField{FC, FT, FR}, Any, ScalarPotential}} where {LN, LD, LR, LC, FC, FT, FR}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::LayeredSpherePEC, excitation::UniformField{FC,FT,FR}, point, quantity::ScalarPotential; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the scalar potential scattered by a layered dielectric sphere with PEC core, for an incident uniform field with polarization in the given direction using Sihvola and Lindell, 1988, Transmission line analogy for calculating the effective permittivity of mixtures with spherical multilayer scatterers\n\nThe point and returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Union{Tuple{FR}, Tuple{FT}, Tuple{FC}, Tuple{LC}, Tuple{LR}, Tuple{LN}, Tuple{LayeredSphere{LN, LR, LC}, UniformField{FC, FT, FR}, Any, ElectricField}} where {LN, LR, LC, FC, FT, FR}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::LayeredSphere, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ElectricField; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the electric field scattered by a layered dielectric sphere, for an incident uniform field with polarization in the given direction using Sihvola and Lindell, 1988, Transmission line analogy for calculating the effective permittivity of mixtures with spherical multilayer scatterers.\n\nThe point and returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.scatteredfield-Union{Tuple{FR}, Tuple{FT}, Tuple{FC}, Tuple{LC}, Tuple{LR}, Tuple{LN}, Tuple{LayeredSphere{LN, LR, LC}, UniformField{FC, FT, FR}, Any, ScalarPotential}} where {LN, LR, LC, FC, FT, FR}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.scatteredfield","text":"scatteredfield(sphere::LayeredSphere, excitation::UniformField, point, quantity::ScalarPotential; parameter::Parameter=Parameter())\n\nCompute the scalar potential scattered by a layered dielectric sphere, for an incident uniform field with polarization in the given direction using Sihvola and Lindell, 1988, Transmission line analogy for calculating the effective permittivity of mixtures with spherical multilayer scatterers.\n\nThe point and returned field are in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.sph2cart-Tuple{Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.sph2cart","text":"sph2cart(vec)\n\nConvert a 3D (e entry) point from spherical to Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.sphericalGridPoints-Tuple{}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.sphericalGridPoints","text":"patternPoints(;r=1.0, resolution=5)\n\nConvenience function returning points (in Cartesian and spherical coordinates) on a spherical grid at a distance 'r' and a resolution in degrees. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.thetaCutPoints-Tuple{Any}","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.thetaCutPoints","text":"thetaCutPoints(ϑ; r=1.0, resolution=1)\n\nConvenience function returning points (in Cartesian coordinates) on a theta cut at a distance 'r' and a resolution in degrees. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"apiref/#SphericalScattering.translate-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Any, StaticArraysCore.SVector{3, T}}} where T","page":"API Reference","title":"SphericalScattering.translate","text":"translate(points, translation::SVector{3,T})\n\nTranslate the points in the direction of the translation vector. \n\nAll inputs are assumed to be in Cartesian coordinates.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#uniformEx","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"<figure>\n  <img\n    src=\"../assets/PECsphere.svg\"\n    alt=\"Setup\"\n    width=\"300\" />\n\n  <figcaption>\n    Setup for the excitation with a uniform static field. TODO: more suitable image.\n  </figcaption>\n</figure>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#Definition","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Definition","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"The static electric field with amplitude a and direction hatbm p is given by","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"bm e(bm r) = a  hat bm p ","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#uniformAPI","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"The API provides the following constructor with default values:","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"UniformField","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#SphericalScattering.UniformField","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"SphericalScattering.UniformField","text":"ex = UniformField(; \n    embedding=Medium(ε0, μ0), \n    amplitude=1.0, \n    direction=SVector{3,typeof(amplitude)}(1.0, 0.0, 0.0)\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"tip: Tip\nThe direction vector is automatically normalized to a unit vector during the initialization.","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#Incident-Field","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Incident Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"The electric field is as given above. ","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#API","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"Φ = field(ex, ScalarPotential(point_cart))\n\nE = field(ex, ElectricField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#Scattered-Field","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Scattered Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"The scattered field computation follows [3]. ","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#API-2","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"The following API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"Φ = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ScalarPotential(point_cart))\n\nE = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"For the dielectric sphere with thin impedance layer two additional quantities are available:","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"Φ = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ScalarPotentialJump(point_cart))\n\nE = scatteredfield(sp, ex, DisplacementField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#Total-Field","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Total Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"uniformStatic/#API-3","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"The following API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"uniformStatic/","page":"Uniform Static Field","title":"Uniform Static Field","text":"Φ = field(sp, ex, ScalarPotential(point_cart))\n\nE = field(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/#Contributing","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"In order to contribute to this package directly create a pull request against the master branch. Before doing so please: ","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"Follow the style of the surrounding code.\nSupplement the documentation.\nWrite tests and check that no errors occur.","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/#Style","page":"Contributing","title":"Style","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"For a consistent style the JuliaFormatter.jl package is used which enforces the style defined in the .JuliaFormatter.toml file. To follow this style simply run","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"using JuliaFormatter\nformat(pkgdir(SphericalScattering))","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"note: Note\nThat all files follow the JuliaFormatter style is tested during the unit tests. Hence, do not forget to execute the two lines above. Otherwise, the tests are likely to not pass.","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/#Documentation","page":"Contributing","title":"Documentation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"Add documentation for any changes or new features following the style of the existing documentation. For more information you can have a look at the Documenter.jl documentation.","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/#tests","page":"Contributing","title":"Tests","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"Write tests for your code changes and verify that no errors occur, e.g., by running","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.test(\"SphericalScattering\")","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"For more detailed information on which parts are tested the coverage can be evaluated on your local machine, e.g., by","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.test(\"SphericalScattering\"; coverage=true, julia_args=`--threads 4`)\n\n# determine coverage\nusing Coverage\nsrc_folder = pkgdir(SphericalScattering) * \"/src\"\ncoverage   = process_folder(src_folder)\nLCOV.writefile(\"path-to-folder-you-like\" * \"SphericalScattering.lcov.info\", coverage)\n\nclean_folder(src_folder) # delete .cov files\n\n# extract information about coverage\ncovered_lines, total_lines = get_summary(coverage)\n@info \"Current coverage:\\n$covered_lines of $total_lines lines ($(round(Int, covered_lines / total_lines * 100)) %)\"","category":"page"},{"location":"contributing/","page":"Contributing","title":"Contributing","text":"In Visual Studio Code the Coverage Gutters plugin can be used to visualize the tested lines of the code by inserting the path of the SphericalScattering.lcov.info file in the settings.","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/#Plane-Wave","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"<figure>\n  <img\n    src=\"../assets/PECsphere.svg\"\n    alt=\"Setup\"\n    width=\"300\" />\n\n  <figcaption>\n    Setup for the excitation with a plane wave. TODO: more suitable image.\n  </figcaption>\n</figure>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/#Definition","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Definition","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"A plane wave with amplitude a, wave vector bm k = k hatbm k, and polarization hatbm p (vectors with a hat denote unit vectors) is defined by the field","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"bm e_mathrmPW(bm r) = a hatbm p   mathrme^-mathrmj bm k cdot bm r  ","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"where the polarization and wave vector are orthogonal, that is,","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"bm k cdot hatbm p = 0","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"holds.","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/#pwAPI","page":"Plane Wave","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"The API provides the following constructor with default values:","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"planeWave","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/#SphericalScattering.planeWave","page":"Plane Wave","title":"SphericalScattering.planeWave","text":"ex = planeWave(;\n        embedding    = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency    = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude    = 1.0,\n        direction    = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n        polarization = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(1.0, 0.0, 0.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\nex = planeWave(\n        sp::Sphere;\n        frequency    = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude    = 1.0,\n        direction    = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n        polarization = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(1.0, 0.0, 0.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"note: Note\nThe provided direction and the polarization vectors have to be orthogonal. This is checked during initialization.","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"tip: Tip\nThe direction and the polarization vectors are each automatically normalized to unit vectors during the initialization.","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/#Incident-Field","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Incident Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"The electric field of the plane wave is as given above. The magnetic field is given by","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"bm h_mathrmPW(bm r) = cfracaZ_mathrmF (hatbm k times hatbm p)  mathrme^-mathrmj bm k cdot bm r","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"with Z_mathrmF = sqrtmu  varepsilon.","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/#API","page":"Plane Wave","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"E  = field(ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(ex, MagneticField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"note: Note\nThe far-field of a plane wave is not defined.","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/#Scattered-Field","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Scattered Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"The scattered field computation follows [1, pp. 347ff]. ","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"note: Note\nInternal details of the computations: Following [1, pp. 347ff] the plane wave is initially assumed to travel in positive z-axis direction and to have a polarization along the positive x-axis. Arbitrary directions and orientations (forming a valid pair) are obtained via rotations. ","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/#API-2","page":"Plane Wave","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"E  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/#Total-Field","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Total Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"planeWave/#API-3","page":"Plane Wave","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"E  = field(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"planeWave/","page":"Plane Wave","title":"Plane Wave","text":"note: Note\nThe total far-field is not defined (since the incident far-field is not defined).","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#Dipoles","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"<figure>\n  <img\n    src=\"../assets/Fig_SphereDP.svg\"\n    alt=\"Setup\"\n    width=\"300\" />\n\n  <figcaption>\n    Setup for the excitation with a Hertzian or a Fitzgerald dipole.\n  </figcaption>\n</figure>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#Definition","page":"Dipoles","title":"Definition","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"The dipoles are defined as infinitesimal time harmonic current elements. Note that the definitions differ from the ones employed in [4, pp. 411ff] basically by a factor of k. Hence, they lead to different static fields, i.e., for krightarrow 0.","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#Hertzian-Dipole","page":"Dipoles","title":"Hertzian Dipole","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"The Hertzian dipole with dipole length l, electric current I, and orientation hatbm p at position bm r_0 is assumed to have the current density","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"bmj_mathrmHD = Il hatbm p delta (bm r - bm r_0) ","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"where delta denotes the Dirac delta distribution.","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#Fitzgeral-Dipole","page":"Dipoles","title":"Fitzgeral Dipole","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"The Fitzgerald (magnetic) dipole with dipole length l, magnetic current M, and orientation hatbm p at position bm r_0 is assumed to have the current density","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"bmm_mathrmFD = Ml hatbm p delta (bm r - bm r_0) ","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#dipolesAPI","page":"Dipoles","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"The API provides the following constructors with default values:","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"HertzianDipole\nFitzgeraldDipole","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#SphericalScattering.HertzianDipole","page":"Dipoles","title":"SphericalScattering.HertzianDipole","text":"ex = HertzianDipole(\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        position    = error(\"missing argument `position`\"),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"dipoles/#SphericalScattering.FitzgeraldDipole","page":"Dipoles","title":"SphericalScattering.FitzgeraldDipole","text":"ex = FitzgeraldDipole(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        position    = error(\"missing argument `position`\"),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"tip: Tip\nThe orientation vector is automatically normalized to a unit vector during the initialization.","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#Radiated-Field","page":"Dipoles","title":"Radiated Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"The electric field of the Hertzian dipole itself (without scatterer) is [4, pp. 411ff]","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"bm e(bm r) = Z_mathrmF cfracIl4 pi mathrme^-mathrmj k r  left( cfrackr  ((hatbm n times hatbm p) times hatbm n) + left(cfrac1k r^3 + cfracmathrmjr^2 right)  (3 hatbm n (hatbm n cdot hatbm p) - hatbm p) right)","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"with Z_mathrmF = sqrtmu  varepsilon and the magnetic field","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"bm h(bm r) = cfracIl4 pi cfracmathrme^-mathrmj k r r  left(k + cfrac1mathrmj r right) (hatbm n times hatbm p)","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"where","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"hatbm n = cfracbm r - bm r_0bm r - bm r_0","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"note: Note\nThe fields of the Fitzgerald dipole follow from the duality relations.","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#API","page":"Dipoles","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"E  = field(ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = field(ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#Scattered-Field","page":"Dipoles","title":"Scattered Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"The scattered field computation is a generalization of the analysis in [1, pp. 374ff]. For the magnetic dipole duality relations are employed.","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"tip: Tip\nFor the scattered field computation the orientation of the dipole is restricted: the dipole has to be perpendicular to the surface of the sphere. This can be achieved, e.g., by defining the orientation firstorientation = normalize(SVector(0.0,1.0,1.0))and then setting the position as a multiple of the orientaion:position = 2.0 * orientation","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"note: Note\nInternal details of the computations: Following [1, pp. 347ff] the dipoles are initially assumed to be aligned with the z-axis. Arbitrary positions and orientations (forming a valid pair) are obtained via rotations.","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#API-2","page":"Dipoles","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"E  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/#Total-Field","page":"Dipoles","title":"Total Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/#API-3","page":"Dipoles","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"dipoles/","page":"Dipoles","title":"Dipoles","text":"E  = field(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = field(sp, ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"details/#Further-Details","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"details/#Units","page":"Further Details","title":"Units","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"SI units are employed everywhere.","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"details/#dualityRelations","page":"Further Details","title":"Duality Relations","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"In many places the duality relations [1, p. 120]","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"electric current rightarrow magnetic current\nbm e rightarrow bm h\nbm h rightarrow -bm e\nvarepsilon rightarrow mu\nmu rightarrow varepsilon","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"are employed in order to compute, e.g., the field of the magnetic current counterparts to the electric currents.","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"details/#rotationDetails","page":"Further Details","title":"Rotations","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"Due to the rotational symmetry the fields for different orientations of the excitations can be computed via rotations.","category":"page"},{"location":"details/#Plane-Wave","page":"Further Details","title":"Plane Wave","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"A plane wave excitation with arbitrary direction hatbm k and polarization hatbm p (forming a valid combination)  can be related to the case hatbm k = hatbm e_z and polarization hatbm p = hatbm e_x by a rotation matrix","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"bm R = beginbmatrix hatbm p  hatbm k times hatbm p  hatbm k  endbmatrix ","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"It constitutes a change from one right-handed orthogonal basis (hatbm e_x^prime  hatbm e_y^prime hatbm e_z^prime ) to another right-handed orthogonal basis (hatbm e_x = hatbm p hatbm e_y = hatbm k times hatbm p hatbm e_z = hatbm k. Hence, bm R relates vectors (and points) bm v in the primed coordinate system (xyz) to vectors (and points) bm v in the unprimed one (xyz) by ","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"bm v = bm R  bm v qquad textand qquad bm v = bm R^mathrmT  bm v","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"leveraging that bm R^-1 = bm R^mathrmT.","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"details/#Ring-Currents-and-Dipoles","page":"Further Details","title":"Ring-Currents and Dipoles","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"Ring-currents and dipoles are characterized by only one vector hatbm p (defining the orientation). An arbitrary hatbm p can be related to an initial one hatbm p_0 (e.g., hatbm p_0 = hatbm e_z^prime) by a  right-handed rotation around a rotation axis hatbm a = (a_x a_y a_z) by an angle alpha. The rotation axis is given by","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"hatbm a = cfrachatbm p_0 times hatbm phatbm p_0 times hatbm p","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"and the angle alpha is encoded in","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"cos(alpha) = hatbm p_0 cdot hatbm p qquad textand qquad sin(alpha) = hatbm p_0 times hatbm p","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"The rotation matrix is then found by the Rodrigues' rotation formula as","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"bm R = mathbfI + sin(alpha)bmK + (1 - cos(alpha)) bmK^2","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"with","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"bm K = beginbmatrix 0  -a_z  a_y  a_z  0  -a_x  -a_y  a_x  0 endbmatrix ","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"Vectors (and points) bm v in the initial coordinate system (xyz) (with, e.g., hatbm e_z^prime = hatbm p_0) are then related to vectors (and points) bm v in the unprimed one (xyz) by ","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"bm v = bm R  bm v qquad textand qquad bm v = bm R^mathrmT  bm v","category":"page"},{"location":"details/","page":"Further Details","title":"Further Details","text":"leveraging that bm R^-1 = bm R^mathrmT.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#General-Usage","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"The basic building blocks are introduced in the following simple example; more details are provided afterwards:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Introductory-Example:-Plane-Wave","page":"General Usage","title":"Introductory Example: Plane Wave","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"using SphericalScattering, StaticArrays\n\n# define excitation: plane wave travelling in positive z-direction with x-polarization\nex = planeWave(frequency=10e6) # Hz\n\n# define scatterer: PEC sphere\nsp = PECSphere(radius = 1.0)\n\n# define an observation point\npoint_cart = [SVector(2.0, 2.0, 3.2)] \n\n# compute scattered fields\nE  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\nH  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\nFF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, FarField(point_cart))\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Defining-Observation-Points","page":"General Usage","title":"Defining Observation Points","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"In order to define points the StaticArrays package has to be used.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"using StaticArrays\n\n# defining a single point\npoint_cart = [SVector(2.0, 2.0, 3.2)] \n\n# defining multiple points (along a line)\npoint_cart = [SVector(5.0, 5.0, z) for z in -2:0.2:2]\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"info: Info\nA Cartesian basis is used for all coordinates and field components!","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Defining-an-Excitation","page":"General Usage","title":"Defining an Excitation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"For all available excitations a simple constructor with keyword arguments and default values is available. For more details see the APIs of the ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"Plane wave\nDipoles\nRing currents\nSpherical modes\nUniform static field","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Defining-a-Scatterer","page":"General Usage","title":"Defining a Scatterer","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"For all available scatteres a simple constructor with keyword arguments and default values is available. For more details see the APIs of the ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"PEC sphere\nPMC sphere\nDielectric sphere\nMultilayer dielectric sphere\nMultilayer dielectric sphere with PEC core\nDielectric sphere with thin impedance layer ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Computing-Fields","page":"General Usage","title":"Computing Fields","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"The incident, scattered, and total fields can be computed.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Incident-Fields","page":"General Usage","title":"Incident Fields","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"For each excitation the far-field, the electric, and the magnetic near-field without a scatterer can be determined: ","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"E  = field(ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = field(ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"For the uniform field excitation, only the electric field as well as the scalar potential can be calculated:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"Φ = field(ex, ScalarPotential(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Scattered-Fields","page":"General Usage","title":"Scattered Fields","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"For each excitation the scattered fields from a given sphere can be determined as:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"E  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, FarField(point_cart))\n","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"For the uniform static field excitation, only the electric field as well as the scalar potential can be calculated:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"Φ = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ScalarPotential(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"For the dielectric sphere with thin impedance layer two additional quantities are available:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"Φ = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ScalarPotentialJump(point_cart))\n\nE = scatteredfield(sp, ex, DisplacementField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Total-Fields","page":"General Usage","title":"Total Fields","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"For each excitation the total fields in the presence of a given sphere can be determined as:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"E  = field(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = field(sp, ex, FarField(point_cart))\n","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"For the uniform field excitation, only the electric field as well as the scalar potential can be calculated:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"Φ = field(sp, ex, ScalarPotential(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Conversion-Between-Bases","page":"General Usage","title":"Conversion Between Bases","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"Methods are provided to convert between Cartesian and spherical coordinates:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"point_cart = SphericalScattering.sph2cart.(point_sph)\n\npoint_sph  = SphericalScattering.cart2sph.(point_cart)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"Converting fields:","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"F_cart = SphericalScattering.convertSpherical2Cartesian.(F_sph,  point_sph)\n\nF_sph  = SphericalScattering.convertCartesian2Spherical.(F_cart, point_sph)","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#Plotting-Fields","page":"General Usage","title":"Plotting Fields","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"To visualize far-fields and near-fields the functions","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"sphericalGridPoints\nphiCutPoints\nthetaCutPoints","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/#SphericalScattering.sphericalGridPoints","page":"General Usage","title":"SphericalScattering.sphericalGridPoints","text":"patternPoints(;r=1.0, resolution=5)\n\nConvenience function returning points (in Cartesian and spherical coordinates) on a spherical grid at a distance 'r' and a resolution in degrees. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"manual/#SphericalScattering.phiCutPoints","page":"General Usage","title":"SphericalScattering.phiCutPoints","text":"phiCutPoints(ϕ; r=1.0, resolution=1)\n\nConvenience function returning points (in Cartesian coordinates) on a phi cut at a distance 'r' and a resolution in degrees. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"manual/#SphericalScattering.thetaCutPoints","page":"General Usage","title":"SphericalScattering.thetaCutPoints","text":"thetaCutPoints(ϑ; r=1.0, resolution=1)\n\nConvenience function returning points (in Cartesian coordinates) on a theta cut at a distance 'r' and a resolution in degrees. \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"as well as the functions","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"plotff(F, points_sph; scale=\"log\", normalize=true, type=\"abs\")\n\nplotffcut(F, points; scale=\"log\", normalize=true, format=\"polar\")","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"are provided (after loading the PlotlyJS package).  For more details see the visualization of fields examples.","category":"page"},{"location":"manual/","page":"General Usage","title":"General Usage","text":"warning: Warning\nIssues have been reported with PlotlyJS if an installation via Conda is employed. See, e.g., this thread for issues with Julia and Conda.","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#Spherical-Modes","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"<figure>\n  <img\n    src=\"../assets/PECsphere.svg\"\n    alt=\"Setup\"\n    width=\"300\" />\n\n  <figcaption>\n    Setup for the excitation with spherical modes. TODO: more suitable image.\n  </figcaption>\n</figure>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"info: Info\nSo far only single modes (not their superposition) are implemented.","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#Definition","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Definition","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The spherical modes are defined following the conventions of [5], however adapted to the time convention mathrme^mathrmjomega t.","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#TE-Modes","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"TE Modes","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The functions","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"beginaligned\nbmf_1mn^(c)(rvartheta varphi) = cfrac12pi cfrac1n(n+1)left(-fracmmright)^m \n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tleft(mathrmh_n^(c)(kr)fracmathrmjmbarmathrmP_n^m(cosvartheta)sinvarthetamathrme^mathrmjmvarphi bme_vartheta   \tright\t \t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tleft -mathrmh_n^(c)(kr)cfracmathrmd barmathrmP_n^m(cosvartheta) mathrmdvartheta mathrme^mathrmjmvarphi bme_varphi  \tright)\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"form the mathrmTE_mn modes, where mathrmP_n^m denote the associated Legendre polynomials and mathrmh_n^(c)(x) denote the spherical Hankel functions.","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#TM-Modes","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"TM Modes","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The functions","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"beginaligned\nbmf_2mn^(c)(rvartheta varphi) = cfrac12pi cfrac1n(n+1)left(-fracmmright)^m Bigg(cfracn(n+1)krmathrmh_n^(c)   barmathrmP_n^m(cosvartheta)\tmathrme^mathrmjmvarphi bme_r Bigg \t\n\t\t\t\t\t+ cfrac1kr cfracmathrmdleft( kr mathrmh_n^(c)(kr)right)mathrmd(kr) cfracmathrmd barmathrmP_n^m(cosvartheta) mathrmdvartheta mathrme^mathrmjmvarphi bme_vartheta  \n\t\t\t\t\tBigg frac1kr cfracmathrmdleft( kr mathrmh_n^(c)(kr)right)mathrmd(kr)cfracmathrmjmbarmathrmP_n^m(cosvartheta)sinvarthetamathrme^mathrmjmvarphi bme_varphi\tBigg) text\nendaligned","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"form the mathrmTM_mn modes.","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"note: Note\nBy c=1 inward travelling waves and by c=2 outward travelling waves are denoted.The change of time convention from [5] to the one of this package is achieved solely by interchanging these values. ","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#modesAPI","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The API provides the following constructors with default values:","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"SphericalModeTE\nSphericalModeTM","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#SphericalScattering.SphericalModeTE","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"SphericalScattering.SphericalModeTE","text":"ex = SphericalModeTE(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        m           = 0,\n        n           = 1,\n        c           = 1,\n        center      = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 0.0),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"sphModes/#SphericalScattering.SphericalModeTM","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"SphericalScattering.SphericalModeTM","text":"ex = SphericalModeTM(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        m           = 0,\n        n           = 1,\n        c           = 1,\n        center      = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 0.0),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#Incident-Field","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Incident Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The electric field is given by","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"bm e^mathrmTEinc_mn = k sqrtZ_mathrmF bmf_1mn^(1)","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"and ","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"bm e^mathrmTMinc_mn = k sqrtZ_mathrmF bmf_2mn^(1)","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The magnetic field is given by","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"bm h^mathrmTEinc_mn = cfracmathrmj ksqrtZ_mathrmF bmf_1mn^(1)","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"and ","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"bm h^mathrmTMinc_mn = cfracmathrmj ksqrtZ_mathrmF bmf_2mn^(1)","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"note: Note\nThe modes are assumed to travel towards the origin.","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#API","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"E  = field(ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = field(ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"note: Note\nThe far-field for a spherical mode makes only sense when travelling outwards.","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#Scattered-Field","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Scattered Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"Matching incoming and outcoming waves to fulfull the boundary condition bm e_mathrmtan = bm 0 yields the scattering coefficients","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"xi_mathrmTE = -cfracmathrmH^(2)_n + 05(k a)mathrmH^(1)_n + 05(k a)","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"and","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"xi_mathrmTM = -cfracmathrmH^(2)_n + 05(k a)mathrmH^(1)_n + 05(k a)","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"where mathrmH^(nu)_n(x) denotes the Hankel function of nu-th kind and n-th order.","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The scattered fields bm e^mathrmsc are then given by","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"bm e_mathrmTE^mathrmsc = xi_mathrmTE k sqrtZ_mathrmF bmf_1mn^(2)","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"and","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"bm e_mathrmTM^mathrmsc = xi_mathrmTM k sqrtZ_mathrmF bmf_2mn^(2) ","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#API-2","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"E  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/#Total-Field","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Total Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/#API-3","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"E  = field(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"sphModes/","page":"Spherical Modes","title":"Spherical Modes","text":"note: Note\nThe total far-field for a spherical mode excitation is not defined.","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#Sphere-Dimensions","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"note: Note\nIn all of the following setups the sphere is embedded in a homogeneous background medium with permeability mu and permittivity varepsilon defined by Medium(ε, μ). The values μ0 and ε0  are provided containing the free space values.","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#PEC/PMC-Sphere","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"PEC/PMC Sphere","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"The perfectly electrically conducting (PEC) or perfectly magnetically conducting (PMC) sphere has radius r and is assumed to be located in the origin. It is defined by PECSphere.","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"<div align=\"center\">\n<img src=\"../assets/PECsphere.svg\" width=\"300\"/>\n</div>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#pecAPI","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"PECSphere","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#SphericalScattering.PECSphere","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"SphericalScattering.PECSphere","text":"PECSphere( \n    radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"), \n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0)\n)\n\nConstructor for the PEC sphere.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#Dielectric-Sphere","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Dielectric Sphere","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"The dielectric sphere has radius r and is assumed to be located in the origin. It is defined by DielectricSphere. In addition to the embedding Medium(ε, μ) a filling Medium(εᵢ, μᵢ) with permeability mu_mathrmi and permittivity varepsilon_mathrmi has to be defined. ","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"<div align=\"center\">\n<img src=\"../assets/DielectricSphere.svg\" width=\"300\"/>\n</div>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#dielecAPI","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"DielectricSphere","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#SphericalScattering.DielectricSphere","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"SphericalScattering.DielectricSphere","text":"DielectricSphere(\n    radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"), \n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0), \n    filling     = error(\"missing argument `filling`\")\n)\n\nConstructor for the dielectric sphere.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"Here radius is a Float and filling of type Medium(εᵢ, μᵢ).","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#Layered-Dielectric-Sphere","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Layered Dielectric Sphere","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"The layered dielectric sphere has radii r_1 r_2 dots r_N and is assumed to be located in the origin. It is defined by LayeredSphere. In addition to the embedding Medium(ε, μ) a vector of fillings [Medium(ε₁, μ₁), Medium(ε₂, μ₂), ..., Medium(εN, μN)] with permeability mu_n and permittivity varepsilon_n has to be defined.","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"<div align=\"center\">\n<img src=\"../assets/LayeredSphere.svg\" width=\"300\"/>\n</div>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#mlDielecAPI","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"LayeredSphere","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#SphericalScattering.LayeredSphere","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"SphericalScattering.LayeredSphere","text":"LayeredSphere( \n    radii       = error(\"Missing argument `radii`\"), \n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0), \n    filling     = error(\"`missing argument `filling`\")\n)\n\nConstructor for the layered dielectric sphere.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"with, e.g., radii = SVector(1.0, 0.5, 0.25) and radii = SVector(Medium(ε1, μ1), Medium(ε2, μ2), Medium(ε3, μ3)).","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"warning: Warning\nThe order of the radii does not yet match the image!","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#Layered-Dielectric-Sphere-with-PEC-Core","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Layered Dielectric Sphere with PEC Core","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"The layered dielectric sphere has radii r_1 r_2 dots r_N+1 and is assumed to be located in the origin. It is defined by LayeredSpherePEC. In addition to the embedding Medium(ε, μ) a vector of fillings [Medium(ε₁, μ₁), Medium(ε₂, μ₂), ..., Medium(εN, μN)] with permeability mu_n and permittivity varepsilon_n has to be defined.","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"<div align=\"center\">\n<img src=\"../assets/LayeredSpherePEC.svg\" width=\"300\"/>\n</div>","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#mlDielecPecAPI","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"LayeredSpherePEC","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#SphericalScattering.LayeredSpherePEC","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"SphericalScattering.LayeredSpherePEC","text":"LayeredSpherePEC( \n    radii       = error(\"Missing argument `radii`\"), \n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0), \n    filling     = error(\"Missing argument `filling`\")\n)\n\nConstructor for the layered dielectric sphere.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"with, e.g., radii = SVector(1.0, 0.5, 0.25) and radii = SVector(Medium(ε1, μ1), Medium(ε2, μ2)).","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"warning: Warning\nThe order of the radii does not yet match the image!","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#dielecimped","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Dielectric Sphere with Thin Impedance Layer","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"The dielectric sphere with a thin impedance layer of thickness t has radius r and is assumed to be located in the origin. It is defined by DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer. Unlike the LayeredSphere model, the solution is obtained by using an approximation: it is assumed that the impedance is so high that the displacement field is purely radial (see [6, pp. 230ff]). This leads to a potential drop across the thin layer, while the displacement field is constant in radial direction. In addition to the embedding Medium(ε, μ) and  filling Medium(εᵢ, μᵢ), the impedance layer must be specified, both the Medium(εₜ, μₜ) and its thickness.  ","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"<div align=\"center\">\n<img src=\"../assets/ImpedanceLayer.svg\" width=\"300\"/>\n</div>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"note: Note\nThis configuration is (at least so far) only intended for the uniform static field excitation.","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#dielecimpedAPI","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer","category":"page"},{"location":"scatterer/#SphericalScattering.DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"SphericalScattering.DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer","text":"DielectricSphereThinImpedanceLayer(\n    radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"),\n    thickness   = error(\"missing argument `thickness` of the coating\"),\n    embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n    thinlayer   = error(\"missing argument `thinlayer`\"),\n    filling     = error(\"missing argument `filling`\")\n)\n\nConstructor for the dielectric sphere with a thin impedance layer. For this model, it is assumed that the displacement field is only radial direction in the layer, which requires a small thickness and low conductivity. For details, see for example T. B. Jones, Ed., “Models for layered spherical particles,” in Electromechanics of Particles, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1995,  pp. 227–235. doi: 10.1017/CBO9780511574498.012.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"type"},{"location":"scatterer/","page":"Sphere Dimensions","title":"Sphere Dimensions","text":"Here radius and thickness are a Floats, embedding, filling and thinlayer are of type Medium.","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"title: 'SphericalScattering: A Julia Package for Electromagnetic Scattering from Spherical Objects' tags:","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"Julia\ndipole\nelectromagnetics\nfield theory\nMie scattering\nplane wave\nring-current\nsphere\nspherical waves\ntime-harmonic","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"authors:","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"name: Bernd Hofmann orcid: 0000-0003-1435-6203 corresponding: true affiliation: \"1\" # (Multiple affiliations must be quoted)\nname: Paula Respondek orcid: 0009-0005-4892-2711 affiliation: 2\nname: Simon B. Adrian orcid: 0000-0001-8008-6235 affiliation: 2","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"affiliations:","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"name: Department of Electrical Engineering, School of Computation, Information and Technology, Technical University of Munich, 80290 Munich, Germany index: 1\nname: Fakultät für Informatik und Elektrotechnik, Universität Rostock, 18059 Rostock, Germany index: 2","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"softwarerepositoryurl:","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"https://github.com/HoBeZwe/SphericalScattering.jl","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"date: 13 June 2023 bibliography: paper.bib –-","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/#Summary","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"When electromagnetic fields are impinging on objects of various kinds, determining the scattered field as a solution to Maxwell's equations is crucial for many applications. For example, when monitoring the position of an airplane by a radar, the scattering behavior of the airplane plays a pivotal role and, thus, needs to be studied. Analytical approaches, however, to characterize such scattering behavior are rarely known. Some of the few exceptions where at least semi-analytical descriptions are available are metallic or dielectric spherical objects excited by time-harmonic or static fields [@ruckRadarCrossSection1970;@jinTheoryComputationElectromagnetic2015]. In some applications, these canonical scattering problems are the study subject of interest. In other areas, solutions to the scattering from spherical objects rather serve as a means to verify the correctness of more involved numerical techniques, which allow to analyze the scattering from real-world objects, for instance, via finite element or integral equation methods [@raoElectromagneticScatteringSurfaces1982;@harringtonFieldComputationMoment1993;@jinTheoryComputationElectromagnetic2015;@adrianElectromagneticIntegralEquations2021]. Hence, semi-analytical descriptions for the scattering from spherical objects facilitate a reproducible and comparable verification of approaches to solve electromagnetic scattering problems.","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/#Statement-of-need","page":"Summary","title":"Statement of need","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"SphericalScattering is a Julia package [@bezanson2017julia] providing semi-analytical solutions to the scattering of time-harmonic as well as static electromagnetic fields from spherical objects (including the Mie solutions for plane wave excitations). To this end, series expansions are evaluated with special care to obtain accurate solutions down to the static limit. The series expansions are based on expressing the incident and scattered fields in terms of spherical wave functions such that the boundary conditions can be enforced at interfaces of different materials yielding the expansion coefficients of the spherical wave functions of the scattered field [@jinTheoryComputationElectromagnetic2015;@ruckRadarCrossSection1970]. ","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"Other available implementations have a different focus, that is, specific 2D scenarios are addressed [@Blankrot2018], T-matrices are employed for general shaped objects [@artgower20181213225;@schebarchov2021;@miepy2022;@Egel2017], ensemble averaged waves are obtained [@fidgit2020], spontaneous decay rates of a dipole are studied [@Rasskazov20], light scattering is considered employing only plane waves as excitations [@PrahlmiepythonPurepython;@konstantinladutenko2017_248729;@matscat2023;@matmie2023;@piemiecoated2016;@miescatwu2023;@cppmie2022], or only far-field quantities are computed. ","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"In contrast, in SphericalScattering a variety of excitations is available, that is,","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"plane waves,\nfields of electric/magnetic ring currents,\nfields of electric/magnetic dipoles,\ntransverse electric (TE) and transverse magnetic (TM) spherical vector waves, and\nuniform static electric fields,","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"where several parameters including the orientation, direction, or polarization of the sources can be set by the user and are not predefined. The scattered far- and near-fields are then obtained following [@jinTheoryComputationElectromagnetic2015;@ruckRadarCrossSection1970;@sihvolaTransmissionLineAnalogy1988;@hansen1988;@jackson1999;@jones1995] for","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"perfectly electrically conducting (PEC) spheres and\ndielectric spheres","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"all via a unified interface. In consequence, SphericalScattering is a useful (code-) verification tool in the area of electromagnetic scattering for a wide range of scenarios. For this purpose, it has already been employed in scientific publications [@hofmannLowFrequencyStableDiscretization2021;@hofmannLowFrequencyStabilizedElectricField2022;@hofmannEfficientCombinationScalarPotential2022a;@hofmannExcitationAwareSelfAdaptiveFrequency2023;@hofmannLowFrequencyStableExcitation2023;@hofmannInvestigationsLowFrequencyStability2023;@hofmannSelfAdaptiveFrequencyNormalization2023].","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/#Acknowledgments","page":"Summary","title":"Acknowledgments","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"joss/paper/","page":"Summary","title":"Summary","text":"Paula Respondek and Simon B. Adrian were funded by the Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG; German Research Foundation) under Grant SFB 1270/2-299150580.","category":"page"},{"location":"joss/paper/#References","page":"Summary","title":"References","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"coordinateSys/#Coordinate-System","page":"Coordinate System","title":"Coordinate System","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"coordinateSys/","page":"Coordinate System","title":"Coordinate System","text":"info: Info\nAt the user interface a Cartesian basis is used for all coordinates and field components. Internally, spherical coordinates are used as well.","category":"page"},{"location":"coordinateSys/","page":"Coordinate System","title":"Coordinate System","text":"The employed coordinate system uses the following convention for the spherical coordinates everywhere in the code with vartheta in 0 pi and varphi in -pi pi.","category":"page"},{"location":"coordinateSys/","page":"Coordinate System","title":"Coordinate System","text":"<div align=\"center\">\n<img src=\"../assets/CoordinateSystem.svg\" width=\"350\"/>\n</div>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"coordinateSys/","page":"Coordinate System","title":"Coordinate System","text":"<!---\n<center>\n<picture>\n  <source media=\"(prefers-color-scheme: dark)\" srcset=\"assets/SphereEx_white.svg\" height=\"3000\" align=\"middle\">\n  <source media=\"(prefers-color-scheme: light)\" srcset=\"assets/SphereEx.svg\" height=\"3000\">\n  <img alt=\"\" src=\"\" height=\"3000\">\n</picture>\n</center>\n--->","category":"page"},{"location":"application/#Application-Examples","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"Two classical application examples are discussed below.","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"application/#Code-Verification","page":"Application Examples","title":"Code Verification","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"This package is well suited to verify the correctness of more involved numerical techniques to determine the scattering behavior of real-world objects. For example, the scattering from PEC objects can be determined by solving the electric field integral equation (EFIE) by the method of moments (MoM). To this end, the packages BEAST and CompScienceMeshes can be employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"using BEAST, CompScienceMeshes\n\n# --- parameters\nf = 1e8             # frequency\nc = 2.99792458e8    # speed of light\nμ = 4π * 1e-7       # permeability\nκ = 2π * f / c      # wavenumber\n\n# --- obtain a triangulation of the sphere\nspRadius = 1.0 # radius of sphere\nΓ = meshsphere(spRadius, 0.25)\n\n# --- define basis functions on the triangulation\nRT = raviartthomas(Γ)\n\n# --- excitation by plane wave\n𝐸 = Maxwell3D.planewave(; direction=ẑ, polarization=x̂, wavenumber=κ)\n𝑒 = n × 𝐸 × n\n\n# --- integral operator \n𝑇 = Maxwell3D.singlelayer(; wavenumber=κ)\n\n# --- assemble matrix and RHS of the LSE\ne = -assemble(𝑒, RT)\nT = assemble(𝑇, RT, RT)\n\n# --- solve the LSE \nu = T \\ e","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"Now that we know the expansion coefficients for the basis functions we can compute the scattered fields:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"# --- define points where the fields are computed\nusing SphericalScattering # use this package to get points on a spherical grid\npoints_cartFF, points_sphFF = sphericalGridPoints()\npoints_cartNF, points_sphNF = sphericalGridPoints(r=5.0)\n\n# --- compute the fields \nEF_MoM = potential(MWSingleLayerField3D(𝑇), points_cartNF, u, RT)\nHF_MoM = potential(BEAST.MWDoubleLayerField3D(wavenumber=κ), points_cartNF, u, RT) / (c * μ)\nFF_MoM = -im * f / (2 * c) * potential(MWFarField3D(𝑇), points_cartFF, u, RT)\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"The fields for the same scenario can be obtained (more accurately) by this package:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"using SphericalScattering\n\nsp = PECSphere(radius=spRadius)\nex = planeWave(frequency=f)\n\nEF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ElectricField(points_cartNF))\nHF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, MagneticField(points_cartNF))\nFF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, FarField(points_cartFF))\nnothing #hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"The agreement between the two solutions can be determined as a worst case relative error of all evaluated points:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"using LinearAlgebra\n\n# --- relative worst case errors in percent\ndiff_EF = round(maximum(norm.(EF - EF_MoM) ./ maximum(norm.(EF))) * 100, digits=2)\ndiff_HF = round(maximum(norm.(HF - HF_MoM) ./ maximum(norm.(HF))) * 100, digits=2)\ndiff_FF = round(maximum(norm.(FF - FF_MoM) ./ maximum(norm.(FF))) * 100, digits=2)\n\nprint(\"E-field error: $diff_EF %\\n\")\nprint(\"H-field error: $diff_HF %\\n\")\nprint(\"Far-field error: $diff_FF %\\n\")","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"tip: Tip\nWhen testing this package, the packages BEAST and  CompScienceMeshes are used to define several functional tests.","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"application/#visualize","page":"Application Examples","title":"Visualization of Fields","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"This package provides several means to directly visualize quantities of the scattering setup.","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"note: Note\nIn order to make the plotting functionality available the package PlotlyJS has to be loaded. (It is a weak dependency.)","category":"page"},{"location":"application/#Plotting-Far-Field-Patterns","page":"Application Examples","title":"Plotting Far-Field Patterns","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"As an example consider a Hertzian dipole that excites a PEC sphere:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"using SphericalScattering\nusing LinearAlgebra, StaticArrays\n\n# --- excite PEC sphere by Hertzian dipole\norient = normalize(SVector(0.0,1.0,1.0))\nex = HertzianDipole(frequency=1e8, orientation=orient, position=2*orient)\n\nsp = PECSphere(radius = 1.0)\n\n# --- evaluate fields at spherical grid points\npoints_cart, points_sph = sphericalGridPoints()\n\nFF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, FarField(points_cart))\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"The 3D pattern can then be evaluated as","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"using PlotlyJS\nplotff(FF, points_sph, scale=\"linear\", normalize=true, type=\"abs\")\nt = plotff(FF, points_sph, scale=\"linear\", normalize=true, type=\"abs\") # hide\nsavefig(t, \"plotPatternHDPEC.html\"); nothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"<object data=\"../plotPatternHDPEC.html\" type=\"text/html\"  style=\"width:100%;height:50vh;\"> </object>","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"Alternatively, the field of the dipole itself or the total field can be plotted:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"FF = field(sp, ex, FarField(points_cart)) # total field\n\n# --- plot only the φ-component in logarithmic scale   \nplotff(FF, points_sph, scale=\"log\", normalize=true, type=\"phi\") \nt = plotff(FF, points_sph, scale=\"log\", normalize=true, type=\"phi\") # hide\nsavefig(t, \"plotPatternHDtot.html\"); nothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"<object data=\"../plotPatternHDtot.html\" type=\"text/html\"  style=\"width:100%;height:50vh;\"> </object>","category":"page"},{"location":"application/#Plotting-Far-Field-Cuts","page":"Application Examples","title":"Plotting Far-Field Cuts","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"Sphercial cuts can be conveniently obtained by:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"using SphericalScattering\nusing LinearAlgebra, StaticArrays\n\n# --- excite PEC sphere by magnetic ring current\norient = normalize(SVector(0.0,1.0,1.0))\nex = magneticRingCurrent(frequency=1e8, orientation=orient, center=2*orient, radius=0.2)\n\nsp = PECSphere(radius = 1.0)\n\n# --- evaluate fields at φ = 5° cut\npoints_cart, points_sph = phiCutPoints(5) # analogously, thetaCutPoints can be used\n\nFF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, FarField(points_cart))\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"The cut can then be plotted as:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"using PlotlyJS\nplotffcut(norm.(FF), points_sph, normalize=true, scale=\"log\", format=\"polar\")\nt = plotffcut(norm.(FF), points_sph, normalize=true, scale=\"log\", format=\"polar\") # hide\nsavefig(t, \"plotcut.html\"); nothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"<object data=\"../plotcut.html\" type=\"text/html\"  style=\"width:100%;height:50vh;\"> </object>","category":"page"},{"location":"application/#Plotting-Near-Field-Cuts","page":"Application Examples","title":"Plotting Near-Field Cuts","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"The near-field of an electric ring current can, e.g., be visualized in the xz-plane as:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"using SphericalScattering\nusing LinearAlgebra, StaticArrays\n\nf = 1e8             # frequency\nc = 2.99792458e8    # speed of light\nλ = c / f           # wavelength\n\nex = electricRingCurrent(frequency=1e8, center=SVector(0.,0,0), radius=3*λ)\n\n# --- define points in the xz plane\nres = λ/15\n\npoints_cart = [SVector(x, 0.0, z) for z in -5λ:res:5λ, x in -5λ:res:5λ]\npoints_sph = SphericalScattering.cart2sph.(points_cart)\n\n# --- evaluate the fields\nE = field(ex, ElectricField(points_cart))\n\nnothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"To plot the fields a heatmap can be employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"using PlotlyJS\n\n# --- convert data to spherical coordinates\nEsph = SphericalScattering.convertCartesian2Spherical.(E, points_sph)\nEφ = [Esph[i][3] for (i, j) in enumerate(Esph)] # extract φ-component\n\n# --- truncate large values (for plot)\ndata = abs.(Eφ)\ndata[data .> 250] .= 250\n\n# --- plot heatmap\nlayout = Layout(\n    yaxis=attr(title_text=\"y/λ\"),\n    xaxis=attr(title_text=\"x/λ\")\n)\n\nplot(heatmap(x=-5:1/15:5,y=-5:1/15:5,z=data, colorscale=\"Jet\"), layout)\nt = plot(heatmap(x=-5:1/15:5,y=-5:1/15:5,z=data, colorscale=\"Jet\"), layout) # hide\nsavefig(t, \"plotNF.html\"); nothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"<object data=\"../plotNF.html\" type=\"text/html\"  style=\"width:60%;height:50vh;\"> </object>","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"Or instead of the magnitude a snapshot can be plotted","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"data = real.(Eφ)\ndata[data .> 250] .= 250\n\n# --- plot heatmap\nlayout = Layout(\n    yaxis=attr(title_text=\"y/λ\"),\n    xaxis=attr(title_text=\"x/λ\")\n)\n\nplot(heatmap(x=-5:1/15:5,y=-5:1/15:5,z=data, colorscale=\"Jet\"), layout)\nt = plot(heatmap(x=-5:1/15:5,y=-5:1/15:5,z=data, colorscale=\"Jet\"), layout) # hide\nsavefig(t, \"plotNF2.html\"); nothing # hide","category":"page"},{"location":"application/","page":"Application Examples","title":"Application Examples","text":"<object data=\"../plotNF2.html\" type=\"text/html\"  style=\"width:60%;height:50vh;\"> </object>","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#Ring-Currents","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"<figure>\n  <img\n    src=\"../assets/Fig_SphereRC.svg\"\n    alt=\"Setup\"\n    width=\"300\" />\n\n  <figcaption>\n    Setup for the excitation with an electric or a magnetic ring current.\n  </figcaption>\n</figure>\n<br/>","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#Definition","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Definition","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"The ring currents are defined by a circular loop of radius a carrying a uniform time-harmonic current.","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#Electric-Ring-Current","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Electric Ring Current","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"The electric ring current with amplitude I, and orientation hatbm p = hatbm e_z with its center at position bm r_0 = (00z_0) is assumed to have the current density","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"bmj_mathrmrc = I hatbm e_varphi delta (r - R_0) delta (vartheta - vartheta_0)","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"where delta denotes the Dirac delta distribution and R_0 = sqrtz_0^2 + a^2.","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#Magnetic-Ring-Current","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Magnetic Ring Current","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"The magnetic ring current with amplitude M, and orientation hatbm p = hatbm e_z at position bm r_0 = (00z_0) is assumed to have the current density","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"bmm_mathrmrc = M hatbm e_varphi delta (r - R_0) delta (vartheta - vartheta_0)","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"note: Note\nArbitrary center positions bm r_0 and orientations hatbm p are computed by rotations and translations of the corresponding fields.","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#rcAPI","page":"Ring Currents","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"The API provides the following constructors with default values:","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"electricRingCurrent\nmagneticRingCurrent","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#SphericalScattering.electricRingCurrent","page":"Ring Currents","title":"SphericalScattering.electricRingCurrent","text":"ex = electricRingCurrent(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"),\n        center      = error(\"missing argument `center`\"),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#SphericalScattering.magneticRingCurrent","page":"Ring Currents","title":"SphericalScattering.magneticRingCurrent","text":"ex = magneticRingCurrent(;\n        embedding   = Medium(ε0, μ0),\n        frequency   = error(\"missing argument `frequency`\"),\n        amplitude   = 1.0,\n        radius      = error(\"missing argument `radius`\"),\n        center      = error(\"missing argument `center`\"),\n        orientation = SVector{3,typeof(frequency)}(0.0, 0.0, 1.0),\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#Radiated-Field","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Radiated Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"The electric field of the electric ring current itself (without scatterer) is computed as a series expansion as defined in [1, pp. 362ff].","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"note: Note\nThe fields of the magnetic ring currents are computed via duality relations.","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"note: Note\nIt seems there exist other ways of computing the radiated fields. The different formulations should be compared someday.","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#API","page":"Ring Currents","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"E  = field(ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = field(ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#Scattered-Field","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Scattered Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"The scattered field computation follows [1, pp. 368ff]. For the magnetic ring current duality relations are employed. ","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"tip: Tip\nFor the scattered field computation the orientation of the ring current is restricted: the orientation vector has to be perpendicular to the surface of the sphere. This can be achieved, e.g., by defining the orientation firstorientation = normalize(SVector(0.0,1.0,1.0))and then setting the center position as a multiple of the orientaion:center = 2.0 * orientation","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"note: Note\nInternal details of the computations: Following [1, pp. 368ff] the orientation vectors of the ring currents are initially assumed to be aligned with the z-axis. Arbitrary centers and orientations (forming a valid pair) are obtained via rotations.","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#API-2","page":"Ring Currents","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"E  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = scatteredfield(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = scatteredfield(sp, ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#Total-Field","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Total Field","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/#API-3","page":"Ring Currents","title":"API","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"The general API is employed:","category":"page"},{"location":"ringCurrents/","page":"Ring Currents","title":"Ring Currents","text":"E  = field(sp, ex, ElectricField(point_cart))\n\nH  = field(sp, ex, MagneticField(point_cart))\n\nFF = field(sp, ex, FarField(point_cart))","category":"page"},{"location":"#SphericalScattering.jl","page":"Introduction","title":"SphericalScattering.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"This package provides semi-analytical solutions to the scattering of time harmonic and static electromagnetic fields from spherical objects (amongst others known as Mie solutions or Mie scattering).  To this end, series expansions are evaluated. Special care is taken to obtain accurate solutions down to the static limit.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"note: Note\nA time convention of mathrme^mathrmjomega t and SI units are used everywhere.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"#Installation","page":"Introduction","title":"Installation","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"Installing SphericalScattering is done by entering the package manager (enter ] at the julia REPL) and issuing:","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"pkg> add SphericalScattering ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"#Overview","page":"Introduction","title":"Overview","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"The following aspects are implemented (✔) and planned (⌛):","category":"page"},{"location":"#Available-incident-fields:","page":"Introduction","title":"Available incident fields:","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"✔ Plane wave\n✔ Field of electric/magnetic ring current\n✔ Field of electric/magnetic dipole\n✔ TE/TM spherical vector waves\n✔ Uniform static electric field\n⌛ Static charge(s)","category":"page"},{"location":"#Available-scattering-objects:","page":"Introduction","title":"Available scattering objects:","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"✔ PEC sphere\n⌛ PMC sphere\n⌛ Dielectric sphere \n⌛ Multilayer dielectric sphere \n⌛ Multilayer dielectric sphere with PEC core \n✔ Dielectric sphere with thin impedance layer","category":"page"},{"location":"#Available-quantities-(where-applicable):","page":"Introduction","title":"Available quantities (where applicable):","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"✔ Far-fields\n✔ Near-fields (electric & magnetic)\n⌛ Radar cross section (RCS)\n⌛ Surface currents\n✔ Scalar potentials \n✔ Displacement fields \n✔ Scalar potential jump ","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"#Detailed-implementation-status:","page":"Introduction","title":"Detailed implementation status:","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"spheres plane wave el. ring current mag. ring current el. dipole mag. dipole TE/TM modes uniform static field static charge(s)\nPEC ✔ ✔ ✔ ✔ ✔ ✔ ✔ ⌛\nPMC ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛\nDielectric ✔ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ✔ ⌛\nMultilayer dielectric ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ✔ ⌛\nMultilayer dielectric with PEC core ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ⌛ ✔ ⌛\nDielectric with thin impedance layer ➖ ➖ ➖ ➖ ➖ ➖ ✔ ➖","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"#refs","page":"Introduction","title":"References","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"The implementation is based on","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Introduction","title":"Introduction","text":"[1] J.-M. Jin, Theory and Computation of Electromagnetic Fields, Second edition. Hoboken, New Jersey: John Wiley & Sons, Inc, 2015.\n[2] G. T. Ruck, D. E. Barrick, W. D. Stuart, C. K. Krichbaum, Radar Cross Section Handbook, Volume 1, New York: Plenum Press, 1970.\n[3] Sihvola, Ari & Lindell, Ismo., Transmission Line Analogy for Calculating the Effective Permittivity of Mixtures with Spherical Multilayer Scatterers, Journal of Electromagnetic Waves and Applications, Volume 2, Pages 741-756, 1988.\n[4] J. D. Jackson, Classical Electrodynamics, New York: Wiley, 3rd ed., 1999.\n[5] J. E. Hansen, ed., Spherical Near-field Antenna Measurements, The Institution of Engineering and Technology, Michael Faraday House, Six Hills Way, Stevenage SG1 2AY, UK: IET, 1988.\n[6] T. B. Jones, Ed., Models for layered spherical particles, in Electromechanics of Particles, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1995, pp. 227–235. doi: 10.1017/CBO9780511574498.012.","category":"page"}]
